{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649560"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:04:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:04:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18365"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18365"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80959"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11083"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66291"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7418"},{"type":"tags","id":"7465"},{"type":"tags","id":"7466"},{"type":"tags","id":"11447"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25702"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25705"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80959"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical location of the tuberosity of the navicular bone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lateral side of the foot","Plantar surface of the foot","Medial side of the foot","Dorsal surface of the foot","Anterior to the talus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe navicular bone is one of the seven tarsal bones of the foot. It is crucial to the structure and function of the foot, particularly with respect to the medial longitudinal arch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe tuberosity of the navicular bone is found on the \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial side of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E. This prominence serves as an attachment point for the tibialis posterior tendon, which is important for maintaining the medial longitudinal arch of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral side of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - The tuberosity is not located laterally; it is on the medial side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsal surface of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - The tuberosity is not on the dorsal surface; it is on the medial aspect\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantar surface of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - The tuberosity is not on the plantar surface; it is on the medial side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior to the talus\u003C/strong\u003E - While the navicular is anterior to the talus, the tuberosity is specifically on the medial side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The tuberosity of the navicular bone is located on the medial side of the foot.","The navicular bone is part of the tarsal bones in the foot.","The tuberosity of the navicular serves as an attachment point for the tibialis posterior tendon."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66291"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18365"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66291"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-24T10:11:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-24T10:12:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11083"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80959"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4899","links":{"self":"htt